ce:section.ce:para:
Water contact angle analysis was employed to appraise the surface hydrophilicity of the virgin and modified membranes, with the findings outlined in Table 1
                         (the selected images are presented in Fig. 5
                        ). Typically, the surface contact angle is affected by both chemical properties and surface morphology. According to Wenzel's findings, roughness enhancement boosts the surface hydrophilicity when the contact angle is below 90° [70]. On the other hand, enhancing the number of hydrophilic functional groups on the surface boosts its hydrophilicity. As results show, the surface hydrophilicity of the membranes is influenced by NPs loading, and adding NPs to the TFC membrane lowers the contact angle from 73.5° to 67.2° in the TFN-MQ1 membrane. As the MOF NPs content rises from 0.100 wt% to 0.150 wt% (in MPD solution), the formed contact angle between water drops and the modified membranes' surface decreases from 67.2° to 49.2°. Considering the surface roughness data in Table 1, this lessened value demonstrates the superior impact of NPs functional groups (including carboxylate, acidic, amine, and hydroxyl groups) on improving the hydrophilicity of the membrane surface. Although reducing surface roughness could raise the contact angle of the membrane surface, its impact is minimal compared to the influence of NPs' functional groups. Thus, the overall effect is that the TFN membrane's surface is more hydrophilic than the unmodified TFC membrane. The more hydrophilic nature of the membrane surface facilitates water molecules' adsorption and water layer formation, which can improve its water flux value and resistance towards hydrophobic foulants [71,72].
